## Migration: `Thread.Abort` → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Why this breaks

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ (`SYSLIB0006`). `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation**.

### Pattern classification

Your code is a **timeout enforcement** pattern — it spawns a thread, waits, then aborts on timeout. The fix: use `Task.Run` + `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter`.

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // Wrap in a cancellation-aware overload
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(
            token => work(),  // original work ignores token
            timeout);
    }

    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key pitfalls for this migration

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Cancellation isn't immediate** | The `Func<T>` overload (no token) will run to completion even after timeout — the caller just stops waiting. Only the `Func<CancellationToken, T>` overload can actually stop work early. |
| **Must check the token inside work** | Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints in loops/expensive operations, or pass it to async APIs. Without checks, the work keeps running on a thread-pool thread. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | It holds timer resources. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures only timeout-triggered cancellations become `TimeoutException`; external cancellations propagate normally. |
| **`Task.Run` uses the thread pool** | Unlike the original dedicated `Thread`, this uses pool threads. For very long-running work, consider `Task.Factory.StartNew` with `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning`. |

### If the work truly can't cooperate

If you're calling unmodifiable code (native interop, third-party lib) that will never check a token, **there is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort`**. Move the work to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` on timeout:

```csharp
// Last resort for uncooperative code
var process = Process.Start("worker.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

### Caller migration example

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework)
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => ExpensiveWork(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// After (.NET 8) — cooperative version (preferred)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return ComputeResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

The backward-compatible `Func<T>` overload lets existing callers compile unchanged, but **only the token-aware overload can actually cancel work early**.
